      <section xml:id="Jan-25">
        <title>Jan. 25: Operations on Sets</title>
        
        <introduction>
          
          <assemblage>
            <title>Motivating Questions</title>
            <p>
            <statement>
            Here are some questions we'll consider.
            <ol>
              <li>What is the power set of a set?</li>
              <li>What is the cardinality of a set?</li> 
              <li>How do we calculate union and intersection of one or more sets?</li>
              <li>What are the complement and set difference operations?</li>
              <li>What is the Cartesian product of two sets?</li>
            </ol>
            </statement>
            </p>
            
          </assemblage>
          
          
            
            
           
          </introduction>
          
          <subsection>
            <title>Outline</title>
            
            <p>
            Today's material comes from <url href="http://discrete.openmathbooks.org/dmoi3/sec_intro-sets.html#xIo">Section 0.3</url> of the book. You're encouraged to read it before coming to class.
            </p>
            
            <subsubsection>
              <title>Membership and Subsets</title>
              
              <p>
                Recall that if <m>A</m> is a set and <m>x</m> is an element in <m>A</m>, we write <m>x\in A</m>. Otherwise, <m>x\notin A</m>.
              </p>
              
              <p>
                If <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are sets and <emph>every</emph> element of <m>A</m> is an element of <m>B</m>, we say <m>A</m> is a <term>subset</term> of <m>B</m>, written <m>A\subseteq B</m>. The <term>empty set</term> is the set with no elements, denoted <m>\emptyset</m>.
              </p>
              
              <question>
                <p>
                  What would it mean for <m>A\not\subseteq B</m>?
                </p>
              </question>
              
              <exploration>
                <statement>
                  <p>
                    Consider the sets <m>S = \set{1,2,3,4,5}, T = \set{1,\set{2,3},\set{4},\emptyset}</m>.
                    Determine whether each of the following statements are true or false, and be ready to explain your answers.
                    <!-- Fill in the blank with the best symbol, or explain why none of these symbols are appropriate: <m>\in, \notin, \subseteq</m>. -->
                  </p>
                  <ol>
                    <li><m>4 \in S</m></li>
                    <li><m>4\subseteq S</m></li>
                    <li><m>\set{4}\in S</m></li>
                    <li><m>\set{4}\subseteq S</m></li>
                    <li><m>\set{4}\subseteq T</m></li>
                    <li><m>\set{4}\in T</m></li>
                    <li><m>\emptyset\subseteq T</m></li>
                  </ol>
                </statement>
                </exploration>
            
            
            </subsubsection>
            
            <subsubsection>
              <title>Some Special Sets</title>
              
              <assemblage permid="qdP">
                <title>Special sets</title>
                <p permid="Aar">
                  <dl width="narrow" permid="qNJ">
                    <li permid="vcd">
                      <title><m>\emptyset</m></title>
                      <p permid="jxF">
                        The <term>empty set</term> is the set which contains no elements.
          
                        <notation>
                          <usage>\emptyset</usage>
                          <description>the empty set</description>
                        </notation>
          
                          <idx><h>empty set</h></idx>
                      </p>
                    </li>
          
                    <li permid="bjm">
                      <title><m>\U</m></title>
                      <p permid="PEO">
                        The <term>universe set</term> is the set of all elements.
          
                        <notation>
                          <usage>\U</usage>
                          <description>universe set (domain of discourse)</description>
                        </notation>
                        <idx><h>universe set</h></idx>
                        <idx><h>domain of discourse</h><see>universe set</see></idx>
                      </p>
                    </li>
          
                    <li permid="Hqv">
                      <title><m>\N</m></title>
                      <p permid="vLX">
                        The set of natural numbers.
                        That is, <m>\N = \{0, 1, 2, 3\ldots\}</m>.
          
                        <notation>
                          <usage>\N</usage>
                          <description>the set of natural numbers</description>
                        </notation>
          
                        <idx><h>natural numbers, set of</h></idx>
                        <idx><h>set</h><h>of natural numbers</h></idx>
          
                      </p>
                    </li>
          
                    <li permid="nxE">
                      <title><m>\Z</m></title>
                      <p permid="bTg">
                        The set of
                        integers.
                        That is, <m>\Z = \{\ldots, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3, \ldots\}</m>.
                          <idx><h>integers, set of</h></idx>
                          <idx><h>set</h><h>of integers</h></idx>
                        <notation>
                          <usage>\Z</usage>
                          <description>the set of integers</description>
                        </notation>
          
                      </p>
                    </li>
          
                    <li permid="TEN">
                      <title><m>\Q</m></title>
                      <p permid="Iap">
                        The set of rational numbers.
          
                        <notation>
                          <usage>\Q</usage>
                          <description>the set of rational numbers</description>
                        </notation>
          
                          <idx><h>rational numbers, set of</h></idx>
                          <idx><h>set</h><h>of rational numbers</h></idx>
          
                      </p>
                    </li>
          
                    <li permid="zLW">
                      <title><m>\R</m></title>
                      <p permid="ohy">
                        The set of real numbers.
                        <notation>
                          <usage>\R</usage>
                          <description>the set of real numbers</description>
                        </notation>
          
                          <idx><h>real numbers, set of</h></idx>
                          <idx><h>set</h><h>of real numbers</h></idx>
                      </p>
                    </li>
          
                    <li permid="fTf">
                      <title><m>\pow(A)</m></title>
                      <p permid="UoH">
                        The <term>power set</term> of any set <m>A</m> is the set of all subsets of <m>A</m>.
                            <idx><h>power set</h></idx>
                        <notation>
                          <usage>\pow(A)</usage>
                          <description>the power set of <m>A</m></description>
                        </notation>
                        <idx><h>power set</h></idx>
                        <idx><h>set </h><h>of all subsets</h><see>power set</see></idx>
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </dl>
                </p>
              </assemblage>
              
              <p>
                We've seen some of the notation below; we'll see more of it next time.
              </p>
              
              <assemblage permid="WkY">
                <title>Set Theory Notation</title>
                <p permid="ghA">
                  <dl width="narrow" permid="WUS">
                    <li permid="Mao">
                      <title><m>\{, \}</m></title>
                      <p permid="AvQ">
                        We use these <term>braces</term> to enclose the elements of a set.
                        So <m>\{1,2,3\}</m> is the set containing 1, 2, and 3.
          
                        <notation>
                          <usage>\{, \}</usage>
                          <description>braces, to contain set elements.</description>
                        </notation>
          
                      </p>
                    </li>
          
                    <li permid="shx">
                      <title><m>\st</m></title>
                      <p permid="gCZ">
                        <m>\{x \st x &gt; 2\}</m> is the set of all <m>x</m> <term>such that</term>
                        <m>x</m> is greater than 2.
          
                        <notation>
                          <usage>\st</usage>
                          <description><q>such that</q></description>
                        </notation>
          
                      </p>
                    </li>
          
                    <li permid="YoG">
                      <title><m>\in</m></title>
                      <p permid="MKi">
                        <m>2 \in \{1,2,3\}</m> asserts that 2 is
                        <term>an element of</term>
                        the set <m>\{1,2,3\}</m>.
          
                        <notation>
                          <usage>\in</usage>
                          <description><q>is an element of</q></description>
                        </notation>
          
                      </p>
                    </li>
          
                    <li permid="EvP">
                      <title><m>\not\in</m></title>
                      <p permid="sRr">
                        <m>4 \notin \{1,2,3\}</m> because 4
                        <term>is not an element of</term>
                        the set <m>\{1,2,3\}</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
          
                    <li permid="kCY">
                      <title><m>\subseteq</m></title>
                      <p permid="YYA">
                        <m>A \subseteq B</m> asserts that
                        <term><m>A</m> is a subset of <m>B</m></term>:
                        every element of <m>A</m> is also an element of <m>B</m>.
          
                        <notation>
                          <usage>\subseteq</usage>
                          <description><q>is a subset of</q></description>
                        </notation>
          
                      </p>
                    </li>
          
                    <li permid="QKh">
                      <title><m>\subset</m></title>
                      <p permid="FfJ">
                        <m>A \subset B</m> asserts that
                        <term><m>A</m> is a proper subset of <m>B</m></term>:
                        every element of <m>A</m> is also an element of <m>B</m>,
                        but <m>A \ne B</m>.
          
                        <notation>
                          <usage>\subset</usage>
                          <description><q>is a proper subset of</q></description>
                        </notation>
          
                      </p>
                    </li>
          
                    <li permid="wRq">
                      <title><m>\cap</m></title>
                      <p permid="lmS">
                        <m>A \cap B</m> is the <term>intersection of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m></term>:
                        the set containing all elements which are elements of both <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>.
          
                        <notation>
                          <usage>\cap</usage>
                          <description>set intersection</description>
                        </notation>
          
                          <idx><h>intersection of sets</h></idx>
                          <idx><h>set</h><h>intersection</h></idx>
                      </p>
                    </li>
          
                    <li permid="cYz">
                      <title><m>\cup</m></title>
                      <p permid="Rub">
                        <m>A \cup B</m> is the <term>union of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m></term>:
                        is the set containing all elements which are elements of <m>A</m> or <m>B</m> or both.
          
                        <notation>
                          <usage>\cup</usage>
                          <description>set union</description>
                        </notation>
          
                          <idx><h>union of sets</h></idx>
                          <idx><h>set</h><h>union</h></idx>
                      </p>
                    </li>
          
                    <li permid="JfI">
                      <title><m>\times</m></title>
                      <p permid="xBk">
                        <m>A \times B</m> is the <term>Cartesian product of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m></term>:
                        the set of all ordered pairs <m>(a,b)</m> with <m>a \in A</m> and <m>b \in B</m>.
          
                        <notation>
                          <usage>\times</usage>
                          <description>Cartesian product</description>
                        </notation>
                        <idx><h>Cartesian product</h></idx>
                        <idx><h>set</h><h>product</h><see>Cartesian product</see></idx>
                      </p>
                    </li>
          
                    <li permid="pmR">
                      <title><m>\setminus</m></title>
                      <p permid="dIt">
                        <m>A \setminus B</m> is <term>set difference between <m>A</m> and <m>B</m></term>:
                        the set containing all elements of <m>A</m> which are not elements of <m>B</m>.
          
                        <notation>
                          <usage>\setminus</usage>
                          <description>set difference</description>
                        </notation>
                        <idx><h>set</h><h>difference</h></idx>
                        <idx><h>difference of sets</h></idx>
                      </p>
                    </li>
          
                    <li permid="Vua">
                      <title><m>\bar{A}</m></title>
                      <p permid="JPC">
                        The <term>complement of <m>A</m></term>
                        is the set of everything which is not an element of <m>A</m>.
          
                        <notation>
                          <usage>\bar{A}</usage>
                          <description>the complement of <m>A</m></description>
                        </notation>
                        <idx><h>set</h><h>complement</h></idx>
                        <idx><h>complement of a set</h></idx>
                      </p>
                    </li>
          
                    <li permid="BBj">
                      <title><m>\card{A}</m></title>
                      <p permid="pWL">
                        The <term>cardinality
                        (or size)
                        of <m>A</m></term> is the number of elements in <m>A</m>.
          
                        <notation>
                          <usage>\card{A}</usage>
                          <description>cardinality (size) of <m>A</m></description>
                        </notation>
          
                          <idx><h>cardinality</h><h>of a set</h></idx>
                          <idx><h>size of a set</h><h>see cardinality</h></idx>
                          <idx><h>set</h><h>cardinality</h></idx>
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </dl>
                </p>
              </assemblage>
              
            </subsubsection>
            
            <subsubsection>
              <title>Operations</title>
              
              <assemblage>
                <title>Subset and Power Set</title>
                <p>
                  <statement>
                    A set <m>A</m> is a subset of <m>B</m> if every element of <m>A</m> is a subset of <m>B</m>.
                    We call the set of all subsets of <m>A</m> the <term>power set</term>
                    <idx><h>power set</h></idx>
                of <m>A</m>, and write it <m>\pow(A)</m>.
                  </statement>
                </p>
              </assemblage>
              
              <activity>
                <statement>
                  <p>
                    Consider the set <m>A = \set{1,\triangle,\set{5}}</m>.
                    Calculate <m>\pow(A)</m>.
                    What is <m>\pow(\emptyset)</m>?
                  </p>
                </statement>
                </activity>
                
                
                
                
