        <section xml:id="Feb-03">
          <title>Feb. 3: Functions and Reading Discussion</title>
          
          <introduction>
            
            <assemblage>
              <title>Motivating Questions</title>
              <p>
              <statement>
              Here are some questions we'll consider.
              <ol>
                <li>How can we define functions recursively?</li>
                <li>What are injections, surjections, and bijections? How do we tell if a given function satisfies those extra condition(s)?</li>
                <li>What reactions do you have to the first part of M4HF?</li>
              </ol>
              </statement>
              </p>
              
            </assemblage>
            
            
              
              
             
            </introduction>
            
            <subsection>
              <title>Outline</title>
              
              <p>
              Today's material comes from <url href="http://discrete.openmathbooks.org/dmoi3/sec_intro-functions.html">Section 0.4</url> of the book. You're encouraged to read it before coming to class. We'll also discuss the first five chapters of <em>Mathematics for Human Flourishing</em> following on the reading and reflection you recently completed, so please refresh your thoughts on that book as well.
              </p>
              
              
              <subsubsection>
                <title>Reading Discussion</title>
                
                <principle>
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      We'll let the discussion take us where it may, but here are some suggested talking points to get started.
                    </p>
                    <ul>
                      <li>What is matheamtics? What connection do you see between doing mathematics and being human?</li>
                      <li>Think of a time you were captivated by exploring something. What analogies can you draw between doing math and doing this exploration?</li>
                      <li>How does abstraction enrich the meaning of an idea? Give an example from your own experiences.</li>
                      <li>Think of an activity you associate with play. Make a list of all the things you enjoy about its playful aspects. Does your list have analogies in mathematical activities?</li>
                      <li>What role does beauty have in the Christian life?</li>
                      <li>Where is mathematical beauty found in the world?</li>
                    </ul>
                  </statement>
                </principle>
                
                
              </subsubsection>
              
              <subsubsection>
                <title>More Function Examples</title>
                
                <exploration xml:id="expl-birthday-function"> <!--  From Sundstrom section 6.1 -->
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      Let <m>b</m> be the function that assigns to each person his or her birthday (month and day).
                    </p>
                    <ol>
                      <li>Explain why <m>b</m> really is a function. We'll call it the <term>birthday function</term>.  What are the domain and codomain of <m>b</m>?</li>
                      <li>What is <m>\ran(b)</m>?</li>
                      <li><url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emmy_Noether">Emmy Noether</url> was one of the founders of abstract algebra, and also made significant contributions to mathematical physics via her discovery of <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noether%27s_theorem">Noether's Theorem</url>. Her birthday was March 23, 1882. Translate this into a function statement, i.e., 
                      <me>
                        b(??) = ??
                      </me></li>
                      <li>Is the following statement true or false? Explain.
                      <blockquote>
                        For each day <m>D</m> of the year, there exists a person <m>x</m> such that <m>b(x)=D</m>.
                      </blockquote>
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        Is the following statement true or false? Explain.
                        <blockquote>
                          For any people <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, if <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are different people, then <m>b(x) \ne b(y)</m>.
                        </blockquote>
                      </li>
                    </ol>
                  </statement>
                  </exploration>
                  
                  
                  <exploration xml:id="expl-sum-of-divisors-function">
                    <statement>
                      <p>
                        Let <m>\sigma</m> be the function that associates to each positive natural number the sum of its distinct natural number divisors. This is called the <term>sum of the divisors function</term>. For example, the natural number divisors of 6 are 1, 2, 3, and 6. Thus:
                        <me>
                          \sigma(6) = 1  + 2 + 3 +6 = 12.
                        </me>
                      </p>
                      <ol>
                        <li>Calculate <m>\sigma(k)</m> for <m>k = 1, 2, \ldots, 10</m>.</li>
                        <li>Does there exist a natural number <m>n</m> such that <m>\sigma(n) = 5</m>? Justify your conclusion.</li>
                        <li>Is it possible to find two different natural numbers <m>m \ne n</m> such that <m>\sigma(m) = \sigma(n)</m>? Explain.</li>
                      </ol>
                    </statement>
                    </exploration>
              
              </subsubsection>
              
              
              
              
              
              <subsubsection>
                <title>Injective and Surjective Functions</title>
                
                <p>
                  Two important properties functions <em>may</em> possess are that of <em>injectivity</em> and <em>surjectivity</em>.
                </p>
                
                <assemblage permid="GUJ">
                  <title>Injective, Surjective, and Bijective Functions</title>
                  <p permid="xtT">
                    A function is <term>injective</term>
                    provided every element of the codomain is the image of <em>at most</em>
                    one element from the domain.
                    An injective function is often called an <term>injection</term>.
                  </p>
            
                  <p permid="dBc">
                    A function is <term>surjective</term>
                    provided every element of the codomain is the image of <em>at least</em>
                    one element from the domain.
                    A surjective function is often called a <term>surjection</term>.
                  </p>
                  
                  <p>
                    A function that is both injective and surjective is called <term>bijective</term>, and referred to as a <term>bijection</term>.
                  </p>
                </assemblage>
                
                
              
              </subsubsection>
              
              
              
              
              
              
              
            </subsection>
            
