        <section xml:id="Feb-17">
          <title>Feb. 17: Bionomial Coefficients II</title>
          
          
          <introduction>
            
            <assemblage>
              <title>Motivating Questions</title>
              <p>
              <statement>
              Here are some questions we'll consider.
              <ol>
                <li>What is Pascal's Triangle, and how can we use it to calculate binomial coefficients?</li>
                <li>Is there a closed-form formula that allows us to calculate binomial coefficients?</li>
                <li>What are permutations, and how can we count them?</li>
              </ol>
              </statement>
              </p>
              
            </assemblage>
            
            
              
              
             
            </introduction>
            
            <subsection>
              <title>Outline</title>
              
              <p>
              Today's material comes from <url href="http://discrete.openmathbooks.org/dmoi3/sec_counting-binom.html">Section 1.2</url> and <url href="http://discrete.openmathbooks.org/dmoi3/sec_counting-combperm.html">Section 1.3</url> of the book. You're encouraged to read it before coming to class.
              </p>
              
              <subsubsection>
                <title>Binomial Coefficients</title>
                
                <activity>
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      Recall that a <term>binomial</term> is an algebraic expression with two terms, such as <m>x+y</m>.
                      Calculate the following.
                    </p>
                    <ol>
                      <li><m>(x+y)^1</m></li>
                      <li><m>(x+y)^2</m></li>
                      <li><m>(x+y)^3</m></li>
                      <li><m>(x+y)^4</m></li>
                      <li><m>(x+y)^5</m></li>
                    </ol>
                    <p>
                      What do you notice? What do you wonder?
                    </p>
                  </statement>
                  </activity>
                
                <assemblage permid="MXD">
                  <title>Binomial Coefficients</title>
                  <idx><h>binomial coefficient</h></idx>
                  <idx><h sortby="n choose k"><m>n</m> choose
                  <m>k</m></h><see>binomial coefficient</see></idx>
                  <idx><h>binomial coefficient</h><h>objects counted by</h></idx>
                  <p permid="tOG">
                    For each integer <m>n \ge 0</m> and integer <m>k</m> with <m>0 \le k \le n</m> there is a number
                    <me permid="ICf">
                      {n\choose k}
                    </me>,
                    read <q><m>n</m> choose <m>k</m>.</q> We define <m>{n \choose k}</m> to be the number of ways to select <m>k</m> objects from a total of <m>n</m> objects.
                  </p>
                </assemblage>
                
                <question>
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      To what questions that we've considered is <m>\binom{n}{k}</m> a correct answer?
                    </p>
                  </statement>
                </question>
                
                <p>
                  Justify the following identity.
                </p>
                
                <assemblage permid="teM">
                  <title>Recurrence relation for <m>{n \choose k}</m></title>
                  <idx><h>recurrence relation</h><h>for binomial coefficient</h></idx>
                  <idx><h>binomial coefficient</h><h>recurrence relation for</h></idx>
                  <p permid="ZVP">
                    <me permid="UQx">
                      {n \choose k} = {n-1 \choose k-1} + {n-1 \choose k}
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                </assemblage>
                
                
              
              </subsubsection>
              
              
              <subsubsection>
                <title>Pascal's Triangle</title>
                
                
                <p permid="GMS">
                  Let's arrange the binomial coefficients
                  <m>{n \choose k}</m> into a triangle like follows:
                </p>
            
                <sidebyside width="70%" permid="RHw">
            
                  <image xml:id="pascal-nCk" permid="FHz" source="./img/pascal-nCk.svg" />
            
                      <!-- <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                  \foreach \n in {0,...,4}
                  \foreach \k in {0,...,\n}
                  \draw (-\n+2*\k, -\n) node {\(\displaystyle{\n \choose \k}\)};
                \end{tikzpicture}
                      </latex-image>
                  </image> -->
            
                </sidebyside>
            
                <p permid="mUb">
                  This can continue as far down as we like.
                  The recurrence relation for
                  <m>{n \choose k}</m> tells us that each entry in the triangle is the sum of the two entries above it.
                  The entries on the sides of the triangle are always 1.
                  This is because <m>{n \choose 0} = 1</m> for all <m>n</m> since there is only one way to pick 0 of <m>n</m> objects and
                  <m>{n \choose n} = 1</m> since there is one way to select all <m>n</m> out of <m>n</m> objects.
                  Using the recurrence relation,
                  and the fact that the sides of the triangle are 1's, we can easily replace all the entries above with the correct values of <m>{n \choose k}</m>.
                  Doing so gives us <term>Pascal's triangle</term>.
                  <idx><h>Pascal's triangle</h></idx>
                </p>
            
                <p permid="Tbk">
                  We can use Pascal's triangle to calculate binomial coefficients.
                  For example, using the triangle below,
                  we can find <m>{12 \choose 6} = 924</m>.
                </p>
            
