										Describe a time in which you have struggled productively. How can you recognize when struggle turns unproductive?
									</li>
									
								</ul>
							</statement>
						</principle>    
    
    
    
    
    </subsubsection>

  
                <subsubsection>
                <title>More Combinatorial Proofs</title>
                
                <exploration>
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      Use a combinatorial proof to establish the following identities.
                      Bonus points for humor and creativity.
                    </p>
                    <ol>
                      <li>
                        <me>\binom{w}{p} \binom{p}{m} = \binom{w}{m} \binom{w-m}{p-m}</me>
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <me>\sum\limits_{k=0}^n \left(\binom{n}{k}\right)^2 = \binom{2n}{n}</me>
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <me>
                          \binom{n+m}{r} = \sum\limits_{i=0}^r \binom{n}{i} \binom{m}{r-i}
                        </me>
                      </li>
                    </ol>
                  </statement>
                  <solution>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Consider a <m>w</m> volunteers for a committee with <m>p</m> members containing a subcommittee of <m>m</m> members. We can choose the <m>p</m> committee members and then the <m>m</m> subcommittee members, or choose the <m>m</m> subcommittee members and then the remaining <m>p-m</m> committee members.</li>
                        <li>How many ways are there to make an <m>n</m>-person committee chosen <m>n</m> Dordt students and <m>n</m> Northwestern students? On the one hand, <m>\binom{2n}{n}</m>. On the other hand, recall that <m>\binom{n}{k} = \binom{n}{n-k}</m>, so the sum can be rewritten as
                        <me>
                            \sum\limits_{k=0}^n \left(\binom{n}{k}\right)^2 = \sum\limits_{k=0}^n \binom{n}{k} \binom{n}{n-k}.
                        </me>
                        Let <m>k</m> be the number of Dordt students. Then for each <m>k</m> we choose <m>k</m> Dordt students in <m>\binom{n}{k}</m> ways and <m>n-k</m> NWC students in <m>\binom{n}{n-k}</m> ways.</li>
                        <li>This is the same story as the previous one, only now there are <m>n</m> Dordt students and <m>m</m> NWC students with a desired committee size of <m>r</m> students.</li>
                    </ol>

                  </solution>

                  </exploration>
                  
                  <exploration>
                    <statement>
                      <p>
                        Find combinatorial proofs for the following identities.
                        Bonus points for humor and creativity.
                      </p>
                      <ol>
                        <li>
                          <me>
                            n\binom{n-1}{k} = (k+1) \binom{n}{k+1}
                          </me>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                          <me>
                            n\binom{n-1}{k-1} = k\binom{n}{k}
                          </me>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                          <me>
                            n(n-1)\binom{n-2}{k-2} = k(k-1)\binom{n}{k}
                          </me>
                        </li>
                      </ol>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <ol>
                            <li>How can we choose a committee of <m>k+1</m> members from <m>n</m> people and designate a chair? First choose the chair (<m>n</m> ways), then the remaining <m>k</m> members. Or, choose the committee (<m>\binom{n}{k+1}</m> ways), then the chair from among the committee members.</li>
                            <li>Basically the same question as the previous one, only now our committee has <m>k</m> members.</li>
                            <li>Similar question as before, only now we have a chair and vice-chair.</li>
                        </ol>

                    </solution>

                    </exploration>
                    
                    
                    <assemblage>
                      <title>Challenge</title>
                      <p>
                      <statement>
                        Calculate <m>\sum_{k=0}^n \binom{n}{2k}</m> for <m>n=2,3,4</m>. Use these data to find an identity of the form
                        <me>
                          \sum\limits_{k=0}^n \binom{n}{2k} = ???
                        </me>
                        Now prove your identity holds.
                      </statement>
                      </p>
                      
                    </assemblage>
                    
                    
              
