<subsection>
  <title>Outline</title>
  
  <p>
	Today's material comes from <url href="http://discrete.openmathbooks.org/dmoi3/sec_recurrence.html">Section 2.4</url> of the book. You're encouraged to read it before coming to class.
  </p>
  
  <subsubsection>
    <title>Solving Recurrence Relations</title>
    
    <investigation permid="wKZ">
      <p permid="GOF">
        Consider the recurrence relation
        <me permid="elW">
          a_n = 5a_{n-1} - 6a_{n-2}
        </me>.
        <ol permid="tQt">
          <li permid="ZXC">
            <p permid="yAm">
              What sequence do you get if the initial conditions are <m>a_0 = 1</m>,
              <m>a_1 = 2</m>?
              Give a closed formula for this sequence.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li permid="GeL">
            <p permid="eHv">
              What sequence do you get if the initial conditions are <m>a_0 = 1</m>,
              <m>a_1 = 3</m>?
              Give a closed formula.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li permid="mlU">
            <p permid="KOE">
              What if <m>a_0 = 2</m> and <m>a_1 = 5</m>?
              Find a closed formula.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </investigation>
    
    <p>
        The process of converting a recursive definition to a closed form is known as <term>solving a recurrence relation</term>.
    </p>
    
    
    <example permid="sbg">
      <idx><h>recurrence relation</h><h>verifying solution to</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p permid="VXD">
          Check that <m>a_n = 2^n + 1</m> is a solution to the recurrence relation <m>a_n = 2a_{n-1} - 1</m> with <m>a_1 = 3</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="IZr">
        <p permid="Dkf">
          First, it is easy to check the initial condition:
          <m>a_1</m> should be <m>2^1 + 1</m> according to our closed formula.
          Indeed, <m>2^1 + 1 = 3</m>, which is what we want.
          To check that our proposed solution satisfies the recurrence relation,
          try plugging it in.
          <md permid="VCe">
            <mrow>2a_{n-1} - 1 \amp = 2(2^{n-1} + 1) - 1</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = 2^n + 2 - 1</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = 2^n +1</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = a_n</mrow>
          </md>.
        </p>

        <p permid="jro">
          That's what our recurrence relation says!
          We have a solution.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    
</subsubsection>

<subsubsection>
    <title>Special Cases: Iteration and Telescoping</title>
    
    <p>
        Sometimes we can find the closed form by inspection.
    </p>
    
    <example permid="Yip">
      <statement>
        <p permid="CeM">
          Solve the recurrence relation
          <m>a_n = a_{n-1} + n</m> with initial term <m>a_0 = 4</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="pgA">
        <p permid="Pyx">
          To get a feel for the recurrence relation,
          write out the first few terms of the sequence:
          <m>4, 5, 7, 10, 14, 19, \ldots</m>.
          Look at the difference between terms.
          <m>a_1 - a_0 = 1</m> and <m>a_2 - a_1 = 2</m> and so on.
          The key thing here is that the difference between terms is <m>n</m>.
          We can write this explicitly:
          <m>a_n - a_{n-1} = n</m>.
          Of course, we could have arrived at this conclusion directly from the recurrence relation by subtracting <m>a_{n-1}</m> from both sides.
        </p>

        <p permid="vFG">
          Now use this equation over and over again,
          changing <m>n</m> each time:
          <md permid="BJn">
            <mrow>a_1 - a_0 \amp = 1</mrow>
            <mrow>a_2 - a_1 \amp = 2</mrow>
            <mrow>a_3 - a_2 \amp = 3</mrow>
            <mrow>\vdots \quad \amp \quad \vdots</mrow>
            <mrow>a_n - a_{n-1} \amp = n</mrow>
          </md>.
        </p>

        <p permid="bMP">
          Add all these equations together.
          On the right-hand side, we get the sum <m>1 + 2 + 3 + \cdots + n</m>.
          We already know this can be simplified to <m>\frac{n(n+1)}{2}</m>.
          What happens on the left-hand side?
          We get
          <me permid="qAo">
            (a_1 - a_0) + (a_2 - a_1) + (a_3 - a_2) + \cdots (a_{n-1} - a_{n-2})+ (a_n - a_{n-1})
          </me>.
        </p>

        <p permid="HTY">
          This sum telescopes.
          We are left with only the <m>-a_0</m> from the first equation and the <m>a_n</m> from the last equation.
          Putting this all together we have
          <m>-a_0 + a_n = \frac{n(n+1)}{2}</m> or <m>a_n = \frac{n(n+1)}{2} + a_0</m>.
          But we know that <m>a_0 = 4</m>.
          So the solution to the recurrence relation,
          subject to the initial condition is
          <me permid="WHx">
            a_n = \frac{n(n+1)}{2} + 4
          </me>.
        </p>

        <p permid="obh">
          (Now that we know that,
          we should notice that the sequence is the result of adding 4 to each of the triangular numbers.)
	  <idx><h>triangular numbers</h></idx>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    
    <p>
        This example works in part because there are the same number of <m>a_n</m>'s as <m>a_{n-1}</m>'s.
        A technique known as <term>iteration</term> can be used if that isn't the case; see <url href="http://discrete.openmathbooks.org/dmoi3/sec_recurrence.html#kwH">Example 2.4.5</url> of the text for more.
    </p>

    
    
</subsubsection>


<subsubsection>
    <title>Characteristic Roots</title>
    
    <p>
        More complicated recurrence relations require another technique.
    </p>

    
    
    <assemblage permid="nrn">
      <title>Characteristic Roots</title>
      <p permid="cwJ">
            <idx><h>characteristic roots</h></idx>
        Given a recurrence relation <m>a_n + \alpha a_{n-1} + \beta a_{n-2} = 0</m>, the
        <term>characteristic polynomial</term> is
	<idx><h>characteristic polynomial</h></idx>
        <me permid="zUa">
          x^2 + \alpha x + \beta
        </me>
        giving the
        <term>characteristic equation</term>:
	<idx><h>characteristic equation</h></idx>
        <me permid="gbj">
          x^2 + \alpha x + \beta = 0
        </me>.
      </p>

      <p permid="IDS">
	<idx><h>recurrence relation</h><h>solving</h></idx>
        If <m>r_1</m> and <m>r_2</m> are two distinct roots of the characteristic polynomial (i.e., solutions to the characteristic equation),
        then the solution to the recurrence relation is
        <me permid="Mis">
          a_n = ar_1^n + br_2^n
        </me>,
        where <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are constants determined by the initial conditions.
      </p>
    </assemblage>
    
    
    <exploration>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let's use this technique to find a closed form for the Fibonacci sequence <m>F_n = F_{n-1} + F_{n-2}</m> with initial conditions <m>F_0 = 0</m>, <m>F_1 = 1</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exploration>
    
    <remark>
        <statement>
            <p>
            Two observations worth making: first, this technique requires each term in the recurrence relation involve a previous term, i.e., the recurrence must be <term>homogeneous</term>. Second, if the characteristic polynomial has a repeated root, then we won't be able to find solutions for all initial conditions with the general form; it's underdetermined.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </remark>

    <example permid="fMO">
      <statement>
        <p permid="aHw">
          Solve the recurrence relation
          <m>a_n = 6a_{n-1} - 9a_{n-2}</m> with initial conditions <m>a_0 = 1</m> and <m>a_1 = 4</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="NJk">
        <p permid="JJl">
          The characteristic polynomial is <m>x^2 - 6x + 9</m>.
          We solve the characteristic equation
          <me permid="wZu">
            x^2 - 6x + 9 = 0
          </me>
          by factoring:
          <me permid="dgD">
            (x - 3)^2 = 0
          </me>
          so <m>x =3</m> is the only characteristic root.
          Therefore we know that the solution to the recurrence relation has the form
          <me permid="JnM">
            a_n = a 3^n + bn3^n
          </me>
          for some constants <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.
          Now use the initial conditions:
          <md permid="alX">
            <mrow>a_0 = 1 \amp = a 3^0 + b\cdot 0 \cdot 3^0 = a</mrow>
            <mrow>a_1 = 4 \amp = a\cdot 3 + b\cdot 1 \cdot3 = 3a + 3b</mrow>
          </md>.
          Since <m>a = 1</m>, we find that <m>b = \frac{1}{3}</m>.
          Therefore the solution to the recurrence relation is
          <me permid="puV">
            a_n = 3^n + \frac{1}{3}n3^n
          </me>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    
    
    <exploration permid="CYX">
    <statement>
      <p permid="eKI">
        Suppose that <m>r^n</m> and <m>q^n</m> are both solutions to a recurrence relation of the form <m>a_n = \alpha a_{n-1} + \beta a_{n-2}</m>.
        Prove that <m>c\cdot r^n + d \cdot q^n</m> is also a solution to the recurrence relation,
        for any constants <m>c, d</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
      <!-- TODO: Needs solution -->
  </exploration>
  
  
  <exploration permid="bBH">
    <statement>
      <p permid="Dns">
        Solve the recurrence relation <m>a_n = 2a_{n-1} - a_{n-2}</m>.

        <ol permid="BTE">
          <li permid="wes">
            <p permid="Hnr">
              What is the solution if the initial terms are <m>a_0 = 1</m> and <m>a_1 = 2</m>?
            </p>
          </li>

          <li permid="clB">
            <p permid="nuA">
              What do the initial terms need to be in order for <m>a_9 = 30</m>?
            </p>
          </li>

          <li permid="IsK">
            <p permid="TBJ">
              For which <m>x</m> are there initial terms which make <m>a_9 = x</m>?
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution permid="kVt">
      <p permid="VqW">
        We have characteristic polynomial <m>x^2 - 2x + 1</m>,
        which has <m>x = 1</m> as the only repeated root.
        Thus using the characteristic root technique for repeated roots,
        the general solution is <m>a_n = a + bn</m> where <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> depend on the initial conditions.

        <ol permid="xjL">
          <li permid="ozT"><m>a_n = 1 + n</m>.</li>

          <li permid="UHc">
            <p permid="zIS">
              For example, we could have <m>a_0 = 21</m> and <m>a_1 = 22</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li permid="AOl">
            <p permid="fQb">
              For every <m>x</m>.
              Take <m>a_0 = x-9</m> and <m>a_1 = x-8</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exploration>
    
    
    
